{"title":"InteractVLM: 3D Interaction Reasoning from 2D Foundational Models","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Estimating 3D human–object contact from a single in-the-wild image is difficult due to occlusions, depth ambiguity, diverse object shapes, and scarcity of 3D contact annotations. Foundation models largely reason in 2D and are not multi-view/3D aware.","method":"InteractVLM introduces a Render-Localize-Lift (RLL) pipeline and a Multi-View Localization model (MV-Loc) guided by a fine-tuned VLM. It renders canonical SMPL+H bodies and retrieved object shapes from multiple views, uses a LoRA-tuned LLaVA to produce contact tokens (<HCON>, <OCON>) whose embeddings guide a SAM-based MV-Loc to segment 2D contact masks, lifts VLM features to 3D via a FeatLift network that incorporates camera parameters, enforces multi-view consistency with 3D lifting and losses, and back-projects 2D masks to 3D contact on meshes/point clouds. This reduces reliance on full 3D supervision and outperforms prior work (e.g., F1 75.6% vs 55.0 on DAMON) while remaining data-efficient (e.g., strong performance with 1–5% of data)."},{"problem":"Existing human-contact predictors are typically binary and do not capture which specific object the body is contacting, limiting modeling of multi-object interactions.","method":"The paper introduces the Semantic Human Contact task: predict body contact conditioned on an object’s semantic label. InteractVLM prompts the VLM with the image and object label; the VLM outputs specialized contact tokens whose embeddings condition MV-Loc to localize contact regions on the body specific to the named object. This yields large gains over a Semantic-DECO baseline across categories on DAMON (e.g., higher F1 and lower geodesic error)."},{"problem":"Recovering joint 3D human–object arrangements from a single image is ill-posed; prior methods often assume known or handcrafted contacts, struggling under occlusions and depth ambiguity.","method":"Using InteractVLM’s inferred 3D contacts on both body and object, the method retrieves an object mesh via OpenShape, initializes object pose by ICP aligning object and body contact points with normal compatibility, and then optimizes object rotation/translation/scale with differentiable rendering, combining mask and contact anchoring losses. This produces more realistic 3D HOI reconstructions and is preferred over PHOSA in a user study (62% preference)."}]}
